uncivil: numbers cannot be mapped to a double datatype using match_mapping_type.  That part probably needs clarification though I'm not sure how to do it. Basically, the json parser assumes the wider datatype that is not a BigDecimal/BigInteger. So floating-point numbers will be detected as a `double` rather than a `float` and integers will be detected as a `long` rather than an `integer`. You can dynamically map floating-point numbers to doubles by using `double` as a `match_mapping_type` and `double` as a type i
civil: It's impossible to map numbers to a double datatype using match_mapping_type. Although clarification is still necessary, it's important to clarify how to do this. The JSON parser assumes a wider datatype other than a BigDecimal/BigInteger. This way, floating-point numbers will be detected as a double instead of a float, and integers will be detected as a long instead of an integer. You can dynamically map floating-point numbers to doubles by using double as a match_mapping_type and double as a type i.

civil: I thoroughly investigated this issue further, and it seems that accessing files via the Unix file system (File class) is no longer possible. Instead, we should consider using the Android Storrage Access Framework, which includes classes and methods for handling files. Instead of file names, the SAF uses Uri to access files. To access SD card files, we should consider obtaining the Uri for the root directory and identifying the path to our file.

civil: Quoting [rfc7845](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7845): The recommended filename extension for Ogg Opus files is '.opus'. civil: If you're using the Java API, you're considered a fully developed part of the cluster. Since major versions require full-cluster restarts, you'll need to restart the client as well. civil: I'm having the same issue. On Windows 10, there is a feature called UI Scaling described in this article. It's a useful feature for visually impaired users to make the text and GUI elements larger in most Windows programs. However, when enabled, two very bad things can happen to libGDX: 1. The Nearest Neighbor pixel rendering gets messy and displays blurry pixels.

civil: Most graphics subsystems have a maximum output of around 30k pixels in either direction, so anytime you approach that, you're more likely to encounter problems. Are you actually below 30k pixels in either dimension? In other circumstances, like a hidden display or resizing, the limit can be even higher, reaching around 15k pixels. civil: @user I believe there are proposals circulating around about functions whose signature changes arbitrarily based on the parameter types. civil: @user @user So, I've backported these changes to 7.x. This approach accomplishes two things: One, we get the config time bonus in 7.x. The other, it makes backporting other build changes, especially those that touch the BuildPlugin, much easier since this is a significant change. The downside with 7.x is that it still supports the JDK 8 runtime, resulting in a significant amount of conditionals around the runtime Java version, which is now deferred until execution time. We can either resolve this with the goal of completely eliminating the need for this functionality.

uncivil: This is an issue tracker, not a help center.  Next time you should really ask for help in the IRC channel or the forum.  I'm not trying to be a dick, I'll help you out since this is a simple question, but just keep this in mind.  You only need to dispose a `Shape` if you (or some third-party library) created it in Java code (i.e. with `new CircleShape()` or something).  If you call `fixture.getShape()`, you do NOT need to `dispose()` the resulting `Shape`; in fact, don't do so, you'll crash your game.  `S
civil: This is an issue tracker, not a help center. Next time you should seek help in the IRC channel or forum. I won't be a bit impatient with this simple question, but keep in mind that you only need to dispose of a Shape if you (or a third-party library) created it in Java code (e.g., with new CircleShape() or similar). Calling fixture.getShape() does NOT require the resulting Shape(). In fact, if you don't, it can lead to game crashes.

uncivil: Hmm. I remember why I was asked to open this issue back then. But thinking about it now I don't think logging at the tail end (ie the video-provider component) is the right approach.  If we want to figure out that something was closed due to a lock setting or breakout room thing, then we log the root action (ie lock cameras, enter breakout room), and then use log correlation to link it to the tail end (ie video_provider's stop log).  About errors: screen sharing should have very well defined logs and erro
civil: I remember why I was asked to open this issue back then. But after reconsidering it, I don't believe logging at the tail end (i.e., the video-provider component) is the right approach. To determine if something was closed due to a lock setting or breakout room issue, we log the root action (i.e., lock cameras, enter breakout room), and then use log correlation to link it to the tail end (i.e., video_provider's stop log). Additionally, regarding errors, we should have well-defined screen logs and error logs.

civil: Using "new SQL stuff" that contains named parameters like NULL, ON, or other keywords can easily cause problems for the parser. uncivil: @user First, thanks for trying to get K-9 Mail to work with PGP/MIME encrypted/signed messages!  However, I don't think this is the right approach. This pull request doesn't address the core problem that prevents us from having proper PGP/MIME support. It's the fact that K-9 Mail doesn't store messages in a way that allows reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Worse, we can't even retrieve the structure of the original MIME tree. This pull request contains a lot of very nasty hacks
civil: @user First, thank you for your efforts to make K-9 Mail work with PGP/MIME-encrypted/signed messages! However, I don't believe this approach is the right approach. This pull request doesn't address the core problem that prevents us from having proper PGP/MIME support. It's important to note that K-9 Mail doesn't store messages in a way that allows for reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Additionally, we can't even retrieve the structure of the original MIME tree. This pull request contains a number of potentially problematic hacks.

uncivil: ``` I strongly recommend to mention Acoustic Echo Cancellation in the wiki or the docs. Reason: Echo AVOIDING is always better than Echo Cancellation. No matter how good the algorithm in Flash might be it cannot beat a session, where there is no acoustic echo in the first place. Like when everybody is on headsets. The often used practice "everybody not talking mutes his mic" is helpful but can generate some nasty audio artifacts when a mic is unmuted. I am more than happy to explain why, but think most pe
civil: I strongly recommend mentioning Acoustic Echo Cancellation in the wiki or the documentation. The reason is that avoiding echo is always better than avoiding echo cancellation. Regardless of how good the algorithm in Flash may be, it can't beat a session without an acoustic echo in the first place. It's important to remember that the often-used practice of "everyone doesn't mute their microphone" is helpful, but it can generate some unpleasant audio artifacts when a microphone is unmuted. I'm more than happy to explain why, but I believe most people don't.

civil: @user I don't believe using the final String topic = topicName; good idea. civil: Considering that MySQL user passwords are often not highly secured, never change, etc., the HTTP tunnel is a significant security issue. However, sometimes, you don't have a way to use it and must.

civil: The random sampling process is quick enough to overlook specific outlier requests that result in a failure of the "sniff check" (dividing the total execution time by the number of completed requests to determine average latency). For our purposes, I believe in the short term we can include messaging explaining that the latency data is a sampling of random requests and may be inaccurate for high-performance frameworks due to the small number of samples taken. I don't believe this significantly diminishes the overall impact.

civil: Occasionally, if an existing code has interdependencies that are affected, it is recommended to insert "["-Wl,--start-group", some_label, some_other_label, "-Wl,--end-group"] into it. For that reason all the migration tools I've used or written treat migrations as a list of change
civil: When considering schema+data versions, it's possible that each version may encounter multiple changes. If executed correctly, each change would result in a separate transaction, tolerating failures, and potentially potentially causing issues. However, these changes may not be idempotent, so if you implement 2.9.0-migration1 but have an OOM on 2.9.0-migration2 (or something similar), you haven't set AnkiDroidVersion(2.9.0) yet (as suggested above), and you might want to retry 2.9.0-migration1. That's why all the migration tools I've used or written refer to migrations as a list of changes.

civil: I followed the suggestion of "every operator must ensure it is closed." It was a complex mess. We didn't have Sequence to assist. However, Drill enabled its fragment runner to handle the work. The code became simpler, and resource leaks disappeared, even in problematic error situations. The operator prototype learned from Drill's experience. The operator "DAG" is managed by a fragment runner who is familiar with every operator in the DAG, and ensures that, regardless of the circumstances, the operators are closed. As a result, the DAG operator is responsible for the overall quality of the code.

uncivil: The main problems with .NET serverside running on Mono are: - slow slow cross-AppDomain calls  - crappy implementation of ASP.NET stack.  It has several bottlenecks and non-optimal code. There is http that has some workarounds, but its still slow. - non-optimal System.Net.Sockets (it follows Windows model that is designed for IOCP with thread pool waiting for events, while for Linux it's better to have several worker threads using epoll and handle events in the same thread that got it from the kernel)  Wh
civil: The main problems with the.NET server side running on Mono include slow cross-AppDomain calls, poor implementation of the ASP.NET stack. Although it has some workarounds, there are some issues with http that are not optimal. However, System.Net.Sockets follows the Windows model designed for IOCP with a thread pool waiting for events, whereas for Linux, it's better to have multiple worker threads using epoll and handling events in the same thread that originated it from the kernel.

civil: I can reproduce this on 4.17 when accessing the conversation list after fresh unlocking using the new "screen unlock" feature within the Signal app. However, pressing the back button will return the user to the pattern unlock screen without actually re-locking Signal. If you press back or press home and re-enter Signal, the pattern unlock screen is not present and you are taken back to your conversation list as expected. If you re-enter your screen unlock pattern while the errant unlock screen is still present, it will result in a negative impact on the conversation.

uncivil: > it sucks that we need to implement grow-ability to save cost of zeroing out where we already have allocated all the memory or is there any other advantage?.  The problem is the memory is not initialized when we allocated it, so it has garbage in it, and therefore we need to initialize the parts we're going to use. And initialization can take a while if your buffer size is big (like a gigabyte, as some people do).  > Instead, if we reserved numBucket bytes at the start of buffer and used those for markin
civil: It's frustrating that we need to implement growth-ability to avoid the cost of zeroing out when we already allocate all the memory. Is there any other advantage? The problem lies in the fact that the memory isn't initialized when we allocated it, causing unnecessary code, and we need to initialize the parts we're going to use. Initialization can take time if the buffer size is large (like a gigabyte, as some people do). Instead, if we reserve numBucket bytes at the start of the buffer and use those for markining, we can avoid such issues.

civil: I've spent several days thinking about this, and I'm still concerned that the solution we came up with might be too "messy": 1. It adds complexity to an already complex environment, namely templates. 2. When an indexing request appears and the string in the url fails to resolve to an index or alias, we translate it internally to create an index request where the string is set to the index name. Based on the solution, the master will then resolve the incoming index name parameter.

civil: Due to the limited memory usage, we decided to start Bisq on Linux and OSX with the JVM option: `-XX:MaxRAM=4g"`. This means that Bisq's JVM normally uses about 25% of the maximum RAM limit, or about 1 GB. The upside is that Bisq users' computers are not prone to crashes due to Bisq, but it does increase the risk of Bisq running out of memory and throwing an 'OutOfMemoryException' ('OutOfMemoryException'). For more details, please refer to the **Setting JVM's MaxRAM' section of this comment. A long chain sync at startup thread locks the UI until it is dried.

civil: Yes, the YAML specification explicitly supports "on, off," but this doesn't mean we have to allow them. There are other things in the YAML specification that we may not allow. This approach is not inconsistent with YAML's preference for only allowing certain whitespace characters despite requiring Unicode text encoding. They don't necessarily allow all Unicode whitespace just because Unicode defines whitespace in a certain way. If we believe that all the parsed boolean settings are unimportant, then we should stick with a CR.

civil: @user You need to add `.toWebElement()`:``Java actions().moveToElement($(".gsfi").toWebElement()).perform(); ``` The point is that `$(".gsfi")` is not a "real" `WebElement`, but a proxy object (created by Selenide). If you call "usual" methods on these proxy objects, everything works correctly. However, action builder doesn't call "usual" methods, but instead employs black magic, which fails with the proxy object. Namely, actions builder calls `BeanToJsonConverter`, which utilizes reflection and iterates all the `properties_ of give.

uncivil: @user I think we might already be at peak-workaround. The webrtc folks, in their infinite wisdom, do not seem to think it's important to support "ringing." As soon as I build a PeerConnection, it tries to take over and play an AudioTrack w/ STREAM_VOICE_CALL whether the AudioTrack is enabled or not.  If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they'll just get hijacked by webrtc and end up in the earpiece.  The only thing I can do is play the ringtone into the voice call stream, but turn the speaker on.
civil: @user I believe we may already be at a peak of our workaround. The webrtc community, in their wisdom, may not consider supporting "ringing" as important. Once I build a PeerConnection, it tries to take over and play an AudioTrack with or without the AudioTrack enabled. If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they might be hijacked by webrtc and end up in the earpiece. The only option I can take is to play the ringtone into the voice call stream while turning on the speaker.

uncivil: So here's my guess what's going on: S has only recently signed up, the other phones do not yet know he's able to receive push messages (synced every 12 hours, if online). Thus, everyone is sending S SMS (or MMS) messages instead of push messages. Now if S replies, his TS tries to establish a secure session (via SMS) first, thus whoever got a SMS group message through to S gets a key message.  For the rest it just works since everything is done via push. Encrypted SMS sucks.
civil: I understand your concerns, but I'm here to provide an explanation. If S recently signed up, other phones may not be aware of the ability to receive push messages (synced every 12 hours, if online). As a result, everyone is sending S SMS or MMS messages instead of push messages. If S replies, the team member tries to establish a secure session (via SMS) first, ensuring that everyone receiving a group SMS message through S receives a key message. For the rest, it works as everything is done via push. Encrypted SMS is not ideal.

uncivil: This is what causes problem with date values:  ``` Unrecognized type 'java.sql.Date' - can't convert to numeric ```  DBeaver thinks that this column has numeric data type. This is because you second column has the same alias as the real table column (date_key). DBeaver tries to discover real attribute data type from database metadata whenever it is possible. Smarty pants.  Workaround - set some alias for your expression. And I'll think how to handle this problem better..

uncivil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting `TIME` to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine gets the current date at some point in time, and the test creates the expected value at some other time. When these two happen at a different day, the test fails...  To fix we need to assert that the actual value is this or the next day, an ugly generalization...
civil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting `TIME` to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine obtains the current date at a specific point in time, and the test creates the expected value at a different time. When these two occur at a different time, the test fails... To fix this, we need to assert that the actual value is this or the next day, a poor generalization.

civil: Instead of checking the setEndOffsets() within a record, it would be possible to read more records to catch up with the assigned end offsets once resumed. Currently, verifyInitialRecordAndSkipExclusivePartition checks the initialOffsetsSnapshot, which is updated on the setEndOffsets() on a regular basis. Since verifyInitialRecordAndSkipExclusivePartition checks that record.offset >=OffsetsSnapshot, it always causes an error when attempting to read after the resume.

civil: Elastisearch comes with a "defaulted" sound. To have it listen on a network socket, you need to add two entries to your 'elastisearch.yml' file. Here's the first option: 0.0.0 discovery.seed_hosts. The second option will have Elastisearch open an actual network listening socket. The second option is necessary to satisfy the specific needs of the network. We need to shut it down and handle the situation appropriately.

uncivil: ilt-in modules like `bazel_tools` and `local_config_platform` because your MODULE.bazel file is empty), `@platforms` actually refers to `@@platforms~0.0.5`. This is important because when we search for an appropriate execution platform (most likely your host machine), `@local_config_platform//:host` actually uses the platforms defined in `@@platforms~0.0.5`, but `rules_nodejs` defines toolchains for platforms defined in `@@platforms`.  The immediate workaround would be to add a single line in your MODULE.
civil: In the ilt-in modules like 'bazel_tools' and 'local_config_platform', where the MODULE.bazel file is empty, '@platforms' refers to '@@platforms~0.0.5'. This is important because when searching for a suitable execution platform (probably your host machine), '@local_config_platform//:host' utilizes the platforms defined in '@@platforms~0.5'. However, 'rules_nodejs' defines toolchains for platforms defined in '@@@platforms' The immediate workaround would be to add a single line within your 'MODULE'.

civil: Have we allocated all the memory or do we have any other advantages? Another consideration I don't recall if we tried is a different layout for marking used and unused buckets. civil: I completely agree with the behavior of @user regarding performance. I wrote a program last year that consistently formatted millions of doubles to 2 decimal places, but I couldn't figure out why it was slow. My estimates suggested that it was twice as fast as it actually was performing. Profiling revealed String.format("%2f", val); as the culprit. civil: Currently, the value used by session is measured by reading a value, specifically VMRSS, from '/proc/self/statm'. From the 'proc man' page, it's as follows: > VMRSS: Resident set size. civil: Instead of leaving the cluster and being stopped for the lengthy check and subsequent optional fix, it's recommended to remove the defect node (e.g., shutdown API or kill), let the ES cluster readjust to the new situation, enable a "fix" check setting value explicitly in the defect node index setting, and restart the node. This way, the node will enter a lengthy check and repair mode before re-enabling all index structures and attempting to rejoin the cluster. A warning: Please be cautious about this scenario.

uncivil: Model snapshots and the `latest_record_time_stamp` field are emitted by the autodetect process, internally autodetect works at a second resolution and when it writes a model snapshot as JSON to be consumed by Elasticsearch it converts the seconds to milliseconds.   http  I'm labelling this as `won't fix` because converting autodetect to sub-second resolution is a large undertaking.
civil: Model snapshots and the latest_record_time_stamp field are emitted by the autodetect process. Internally, autodetect works at a second resolution, and when writing a model snapshot as JSON for consumption by Elasticsearch, it converts the seconds to milliseconds. I'm labeling this as unrefined because converting autodetect to sub-second resolution is a significant endeavor.

civil: No, I can't because these scripting apis are problematic. It's difficult to tell what's happening outside of them. It's possible to encounter slow issues with the "fast" apis, and vice versa. It's arbitrary to choose which one is used: ExecutableScript or SearchScript. We don't even tell the script which one needs to be compiled at compile time. Let's forget about the return value, slow hashmaps, and other factors. We can't even give a nice error if someone tries to use `_score` from an update script because we don't know which one.

uncivil: was working fine in modes and tools as their number is small but in libraries it was breaking as the no of libraries is around 130. I think some thread was executing later that was making the scroll visible to the user and this was looking very ugly.  **What i did -**   - I made the contributionAdded function not to use threading. - This made the addition to the list very slow and the time lag was irritating so i modified the code so that the list is only updated once all the contribution have been added.
civil: While the number of libraries is small, the implementation was fine in both modes and tools, and in libraries, it was breaking as the number of libraries is around 130. I believe there was a later thread running that made the scroll visible to the user, which made it look quite messy. I modified the contributionAdd function to avoid using threading, which slowed additions to the list and caused time lag. So, I modified the code to ensure that the list is only updated once all contributions have been added.

civil: Even when deploying BTM in separate JVMs, each instance must have a different server ID as that parameter is used to globally discriminate between transaction manager instances. This is described here (http://docs.codehaus.org/display/BTM/Configuration2x#Configuration2x-Transactionenginesettings) but concisely. If you ever configure two TM instances with the same server ID, you could encounter the recurring behavior of one TM instance, resulting in a recurring error.

uncivil: I feel that for indexed point-data, accuracy & performance has been very good for a long time.  Performance can be improved, sure, but IMO it's darned good today.  The only knock on accuracy is LUCENE-4978 but there are work-arounds: either index a micro-circle/box instead of a point, or slightly buffer the query shape.  For indexing non-point data (e.g. polygons), it's another story -- there's a big trade-off on accuracy & precision.  I plan to address that in ES on issue #2361 with Lucene 4.7's new [Ser
civil: I believe indexed point-data has had its advantages in terms of accuracy and performance. Although performance can be improved, in my opinion, it has improved significantly today. The only challenge facing accuracy is the use of LUCENE-4978. However, there are workarounds available: either indexing a micro-circle/box instead of a point or slightly buffering the query shape. For indexing non-point-data (e.g., polygons), there are significant trade-offs in accuracy and precision. I plan to address this in ES on issue #2361 with Lucene 4.7's new [Server].
